caption_original:
Small mussel, big problem. Did you know that Zebra Mussels are capable of heavily colonizing hard and soft surfaces like docks, boats and beaches? They can clog intake structures in power stations and water treatment plants and cause millions of dollars in damages. Zebra Mussels are found throughout all the Great Lakes. 

They are an average of 2-2.5 cm, reaching up to 4 cm long, triangular in shape, and are black or brown with white to yellow zigzagged patterns. If you think you‚Äôve seen or caught a Zebra Mussel where they are not known to occur:
*Do not release it into the water.
*Catch it and keep it frozen. If you can‚Äôt do that, destroy it.
*Note the location (with GPS coordinates if possible) as well as the observation date.
*Contact Fisheries and Oceans Canada: http://ow.ly/v6nI30fzR1P
Click here for more information about this Aquatic Invasive Species: http://ow.ly/XWGZ30fzR9Q

caption_original:
Ahoy! An opportunistic meeting of two Coast Guard icebreakers in the Beaufort Sea in early October, facilitated the transfer of a hydrographer and some science samples from CCGS Sir Wilfrid Laurier to CCGS Louis S. St-Laurent. 

CCGS Sir Wilfrid Laurier had been conducting a mooring program, just prior to starting its journey south to its homeport in our Pacific Region.  CCGS Louis S. St-Laurent was finishing up a month-long science program in the Beaufort Sea before heading to Kugluktuk for a crew change and then sailing on to Milne Inlet for icebreaking operations in the Eastern Arctic before eventually heading to its homeport in our Atlantic Region. 

All missions accomplished; ships, personnel and science samples on their way to their final destinations! Bravo Zulu on a great #Arctic season. #CCG Proud.

caption_original: Ann Harvey (1811-1860). Born in Isle aux Morts, Newfoundland, the daughter of a fisherman and the eldest of eight children she often spent time helping her father. While fishing in July 1828, they noticed debris floating in the water, and realized that there was a shipwreck nearby. Ann Harvey, her father, twelve year old brother, and the family dog went out in their boat to locate the wreck, and found a large group of survivors on a tiny island. The family managed to save more than 160 people, and the rescue became famous across province. Ann Harvey became known as the Grace Darling of Newfoundland (from an English woman who participated in a similar rescue). http://ow.ly/Kbt630dblWW

caption_original:
Canadian Solar was founded in 2001 in Guelph, Ontario, and is one of the three biggest solar companies in the world by revenue. There are over 9,700 employees working in 20 countries on six continents, making it a global leader among clean technology companies. 

In June 2017, Export Development Canada (EDC) announced $91 million in financing to Canadian Solar to aid in the construction of the Mohammed bin Rashid Al Maktoum Solar Park in Dubai, which when completed, will be the most powerful solar power plant in the world.

In addition to the project being groundbreaking in size, Canadian Solar is using innovative practices to maximize efficiency as well. The park will use tilting panels to track the sun, rather than standard conventional solar power arrays.

The park will use tilting panels to track the sun, rather than standard conventional solar power arrays.

If you‚Äôre a boater or fisher, it‚Äôs important to learn to identify Asian carp, an aquatic invasive species. 
The term, ‚ÄúAsian carp‚Äù actually refers to four species of carps. Black Carp have a blunt, scaleless head with a small toothless mouth, and no barbels. They have a pointed snout and a slightly downturned mouth. The body is long and narrow and the dorsal fin is shorter than that of Common Carp. Scales are very large with dark edges, giving a cross-hatched appearance. If you think you‚Äôve found a Black Carp, put it on ice (do not freeze) and contact the Invading Species Hotline at: 1-800-563-7711 (in Ontario), or visit http://ow.ly/QoOk30fUGLu

caption_original:
Did you know that lightships preceded lighthouses to help signal dangerous areas for navigation? From 1830 to 1960, about ten of these ships were used to provide safer navigation on the St. Lawrence River. They were anchored near obstacles where the construction of a lighthouse was impossible. In Quebec, the era of the lightships ended in 1963 and several of them were replaced by pillars.

See more photos: https://www.flickr.com/photos/mpo-dfo_quebec/sets/72157650880831352
